May 1909.

711-717 Seventh Ave., east side, between West 47th and 48th Streets.
About 1910.

Seventh Avenue, at the N.E. corner of West 47th Street, showing the structure housing the Columbia Theatre. This eventually became the present Mayfair Theatre. The Avenue is to the left and shown upon same is one of the distinctive Broadway street-cars.

October 31, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 939

711-5 Seventh Avenue, east side, between West 47th and 48th Street's. To the right is the Columbia Theatre located at the N.E. corner of 47th Street.

October 3, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 866

704-8 Seventh Avenue, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of West 47th Street. Note the bill-boards covering the upper portion of these structures. Atop same is the steel structure supporting the distinctive electric sign, closely identified with this locale, Times Square.

October 31, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 937

West 47th Street, north side, from Seventh Avenue (right) to Broadway (left), showing the apex of the triangular structure that divides these two thoroughfares. This forms the northern boundary of Times Square. Note the distinctive electric atop same.

October 31, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 938

Seventh Ave, east side, north from and including 47th Street, to, but not including 49th Street. The view also shows the convergence of Broadway and Seventh Ave. Also seen is the northern extremity of Longacre Square (or Times Square.)

About 1917.

Eugene L. Armbruster, Collection.
